<div id="review_3558420023" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3558420023" />
    <a title="Lindsay Nixon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3493901-lindsay-nixon"><img alt="Lindsay Nixon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468796179p2/3493901.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3558420023?book_show_action=true">Sep 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lindsay Nixon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lindsay Nixon" href="/user/show/3493901-lindsay-nixon">Lindsay Nixon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3558420023" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2669384409140657892">THIS SHOULD BE READ IN SCHOOLS <br/><br/>It’s an Indian/Hindu/Muslim cousin to The Hate You Give<br/><br/>I highly recommend the audio book for the beautiful accents. <br/>——<br/><br/>my first takeaway was “when will be ever learn?”<br/><br/>My second was “I leaned nothing in European history class” / omg our history books are seriously washed in toxic white patriarchy paint <br/><br/>My third was “EVERYONE READ THIS!” It takes place in 1947 and is still accurate today 😞 <br/><br/>Great choice for a book club—many wonderful issues to talk about!<br/><br/>—-<br/>SUMMARY: 13 </span>
  <span id="freeText2669384409140657892" style="display:none">THIS SHOULD BE READ IN SCHOOLS <br /><br />It’s an Indian/Hindu/Muslim cousin to The Hate You Give<br /><br />I highly recommend the audio book for the beautiful accents. <br />——<br /><br />my first takeaway was “when will be ever learn?”<br /><br />My second was “I leaned nothing in European history class” / omg our history books are seriously washed in toxic white patriarchy paint <br /><br />My third was “EVERYONE READ THIS!” It takes place in 1947 and is still accurate today 😞 <br /><br />Great choice for a book club—many wonderful issues to talk about!<br /><br />—-<br />SUMMARY: 13 yo girl in India starts a journal, which is in the format of letters to her deceased mother. Her parents were/are Hindu and Muslim. Their families did not support their union so they moved to a part of India where many different nationalities and religions peacefully coexisted. <br /><br />Now, it’s 1947 and India is becoming independent from Britain / divided. Violence hits the streets and thousands of people are uprooted from their homes and must travel long distances to their new “home” <br /><br />This book is mostly her family’s journey but it also serves as a meditation on “love is love” and that family comes in all shapes, faiths and colors—AND manages to capture the languages of love and the inter workings of families, and how parents and children see each other. <br /><br />The story is also a positive example for young people who are “different” (she has trouble speaking) or are not what their parents want them to be (her doctor father is angry her brother loves art and struggles at school)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2669384409140657892" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


